{{Infobox officeholder |name = Akbar Ayub Khan |honorific-suffix = MPA |office = Adviser on Communication and Works to[[Chief Minister of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] | image = |image_size = |term_start = June 2013 |term_end = 28 May 2018 |predecessor = |successor = |office1 = Member of the [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Assembly ]] |term_start1 = 31 May 2013 |term_end1 = 28 May 2018 |predecessor1 = |president1 = |primeminister1 = |successor1 = |constituency1 = PK-50 Haripur-II |nationality = [[Pakistani]] |party = [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]] (PTI) |otherparty = |birth_date = |birth_place = |occupation = [[Politician]] }}
'''Akbar Ayub Khan''' (born 17 July 1971) is a [[Pakistani]] politician and businessman.<ref>{{cite book |title=NWFP Political Directory |year=1995}}</ref> He was an MPA representing the PK-50 Haripur-II constituency.<ref>http://www.pakp.gov.pk/2013/member/pk-50-haripur/</ref>
Akbar Ayub was born in village [[Rehana]] in [[Haripur District]] of [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], Pakistan.{{cn|date=November 2016}} He is a [[Hindkowan]] of the [[Tareen]] tribe.<ref>{{cite book |first=A. A. |last=Qazi |title=Tribes and Notables of Hazara Region Pakistan |year=1997 |pages=420–421}}</ref> He was educated at the [[Army Burn Hall College]], [[Abbottabad]], [[Pakistan]], passing high school.<ref>{{cite book |title=Army Burn Hall College Alumni Register |year=1989}}</ref>
Akbar Ayub Khan gained victory yet again in the 2018 General Elections from PK-50 and will be taking oath as a parliamentarian of the KPK assembly on the 13th of August 2018.
