'''''The Diamond Smugglers''''' is a non-fiction work by [[Ian Fleming]] that was first published in 1957 in the United Kingdom and in 1958 in the United States. The book is based on two weeks of interviews Fleming undertook with John Collard, a member of the International Diamond Security Organisation (IDSO), which was headed by Sir [[Percy Sillitoe]], the ex-chief of [[MI5]] who worked exclusively for the diamond company [[De Beers]].

The IDSO was formed by Sillitoe to combat the smuggling of diamonds from Africa, where, it was estimated, £10 million (£{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|10000000|1957}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} pounds{{inflation-fn|UK|df=yes}}) worth of gems were being smuggled out of South Africa alone every year. The book expands upon articles Fleming wrote for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' in 1957.

Fleming was better known as the author of a [[List of James Bond novels and short stories|series of books]] about his super-spy creation, [[James Bond (literary character)|James Bond]]; ''The Diamond Smugglers'' is one of two non-fiction books he wrote. It was broadly well-received, although some reviewers commented on the stories not being new.

==Synopsis==
''The Diamond Smugglers'' is the account of [[Ian Fleming]]'s meeting with John Collard, a member of the International Diamond Security Organisation (IDSO). The book takes the form of background narrative by Fleming of where the two men met, interspersed with the interview between Fleming and Collard, who is introduced under the pseudonym of "John Blaize".

Collard relates how he was recruited into the IDSO by Sir [[Percy Sillitoe]], the ex-head of [[MI5]], under whom Collard had worked. The book goes on to look at the activities of the IDSO from the end of 1954 until the operation was closed down in April 1957, when its job was complete. Collard explained that the IDSO was set up at the instigation of the Chairman of [[De Beers]], [[Philip Oppenheimer|Sir Philip Oppenheimer]], after an [[Interpol]] report stated that £10 million of diamonds were being smuggled out of South Africa each year, as well as additional amounts from [[Sierra Leone]], [[Portuguese Angola|Portuguese West Africa]], the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]] and [[Tanganyika]].

As well as providing a history of the IDSO's operations, Collard relates a number of illustrative vignettes concerning the diamond smuggling cases he and the organisation dealt with.

==Background==
Fleming became interested in diamond smuggling after reading an article in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' in 1954 concerning the Sierra Leone diamond industry.{{sfn|Chancellor|2005|p=84}} Philip Brownrigg, an old friend from [[Eton College|Eton]] and a senior exec of De Beers, arranged for Fleming to visit the London Diamond Club to see diamonds being sorted and polished.{{sfn|Benson|1988|p=31}} In 1955 Brownrigg also introduced Fleming to Sir Percy Sillitoe, former head of MI5, who was working for De Beers and investigating the illicit diamond trade through the International Diamond Security Organisation.{{sfn|Chancellor|2005|p=84}} Fleming met Sillitoe and used much of the research as background material for his fictional Bond novel, [[Diamonds Are Forever (novel)|''Diamonds Are Forever'']].{{sfn|Chancellor|2005|p=84}}

Fleming retained an interest in the subject and when Sillitoe suggested to the editor of ''The Sunday Times'', [[Denis Hamilton]], that the paper may want to write a story on the International Diamond Security Organisation, Hamilton offered the story to Fleming.{{sfn|Lycett|1996|p=310}} Sillitoe also offered his deputy, retired MI5 officer John Collard, as liaison for Fleming to interview.{{sfn|Lycett|1996|p=310}} During [[World War II]], Collard had assisted in the planning of [[Operation Overlord]] as part of [[MI11]] and had joined MI5 under Sillitoe at the war's end.<ref name="Collard Obit">{{cite news|title=John Collard – Obituary|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=13 November 2002|location=London|page=38}}</ref> Whilst in MI5 he played a major role in the capture and conviction of the atomic spy [[Klaus Fuchs]],<ref name="Collard Obit"/> before Sillitoe had approached him in 1954 to work for the International Diamond Security Organisation.{{sfn|Lycett|1996|p=312}}

Fleming and Collard met in Tangiers on 13 April 1957; Fleming considered Collard to be a "reluctant hero, like all Britain's best secret agents".{{sfn|Chancellor|2005|p=171}} The pair spent two weeks discussing the issue of diamond smuggling,{{sfn|Benson|1988|p=16}} with Collard explaining what happened in South Africa and Sierra Leone. Fleming would then dictate an average of 5,000 words a day to a secretary.{{sfn|Lycett|1996|p=213}}

When the drafts of the books were shown to De Beers they objected to a number of areas and threatened an injunction against Fleming and ''The Sunday Times'', which resulted in much material being removed.{{sfn|Benson|1988|p=17}} ''The Sunday Times'' serialised the book over six weeks, starting on 15 September 1957<ref>{{cite news|last=Fleming|first=Ian|title=The Diamond Smugglers: The Million Carat Network|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=15 September 1957|authorlink=Ian Fleming|location=London|pages=12–13}}</ref> and finishing on 20 October 1957.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fleming|first=Ian|title=The Diamond Smugglers: 'Monsieur Diamant'|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=20 October 1957|authorlink=Ian Fleming|location=London|page=11}}</ref>

==Release and reception==
''The Diamond Smugglers'' was published in the UK in November 1957, by [[Jonathan Cape]], was 160 pages long and cost 12 [[Shilling (British coin)|shillings]] 6d.{{sfn|Benson|1988|p=17}}<ref name="Econ (1957)">{{cite news|title=All that Glitters|newspaper=[[The Economist]]|date=14 December 1957|location=London|page=955}}</ref> The book was published in the US on 13 May 1958, by [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] and cost $3.50.<ref name="Barkham 1958">{{cite news|last=Barkham|first=John|title=Dark Dees and Glittering Gems|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 June 1958|page=BR17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The diamond smugglers. With an introd. by "John Blaize"|url=http://catalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?v1=3&ti=1,3&Search%5FArg=the%20diamond%20smugglers&Search%5FCode=GKEY%5E%2A&CNT=100&type=quick&PID=VOZiAkkWlNW3YmaZ3ed4MCCWhCZGI&SEQ=20120506145155&SID=1|work=Library of Congress Online Catalog|publisher=[[The Library of Congress]]|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>

===Reviews===
The book received largely positive reviews. Michael Crampton, writing for ''The Sunday Times'' considered it an "exciting and richly fascinating account"<ref name="Crampton (1957)">{{cite news|last=Crampton|first=Michael|title=Smuggling the Sparklers|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=1 December 1957|location=London|page=8}}</ref> and thought Fleming authored a book that "ringing true as fact, is at the same time as highly entertaining as any fiction."<ref name="Crampton (1957)"/> ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'' obtained the services of the [[Cedric Brudenell-Bruce, 7th Marquess of Ailesbury|Earl of Cardigan]] to review the book. He noted that "the book is put together with a skill one would expect from Mr. Fleming",<ref name="Cardigan (1958)">{{cite news|last=Cardigan|first=Earl of|title=The Lure of Diamonds|newspaper=[[The Times Literary Supplement]]|date=17 January 1958|authorlink=Cedric Brudenell-Bruce, 7th Marquess of Ailesbury|location=London|page=33}}</ref> which leads to something that is "very entertaining reading".<ref name="Cardigan (1958)"/>

Reviewing for ''[[The Observer]]'', [[Anthony Sampson]] thought the book had "sparkle", adding that "it is often difficult to remember that we are not listening to his old hero Mr. James Bond."<ref name="Sampson (1957)">{{cite news|last=Sampson|first=Anthony|title=Monsieur Diamant|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|date=15 December 1957|authorlink=Anthony Sampson|location=London|page=12}}</ref> Sampson noted that the book included "several yarns which are worthy of the best spy-stories".<ref name="Sampson (1957)"/> The reviewer for ''[[The Economist]]'' enjoyed the book, but considered that while many of the stories "make good reading&nbsp;... they are not new".<ref name="Econ (1957)"/> For ''[[The New York Times]]'', John Barkham thought that Fleming's foray into non-fiction produced "mixed results".<ref name="Barkham 1958"/> Although he found the subject interesting, the basis in interview resulted in a "choppy book"<ref name="Barkham 1958"/> that was "no more than an interim report".<ref name="Barkham 1958"/>

==Attempted film adaptation==

Shortly after publication, [[The Rank Group]] offered £13,500 (£{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|13500|1957}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} pounds{{inflation-fn|UK|df=yes}}) for the film rights to the book, which Fleming accepted, telling them he would write a full story outline for an extra £1,000.{{sfn|Lycett|1996|p=317}} Several contemporary newspaper reports referred to the project as "The Diamond Spy".<ref name="Duns (2010)" /> British producer George Willoughby subsequently obtained the rights for the book from Rank and tried to make a film with the actor [[Richard Todd]], eventually commissioning a screenplay from Australian writer [[Jon Cleary]], who finished a script in October 1964 that remained faithful in spirit to Fleming's book while also featuring elements familiar from the [[James Bond]] films.<ref name="Duns (2010)">{{cite news|last=Duns|first=Jeremy|title=Ian Fleming's book about gem smuggling in South Africa is as thrilling as Bond, and should have been a blockbuster film starring Steve McQueen. So what went wrong?|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=7 March 2010|authorlink=Jeremy Duns|location=London|pages=4–5}}</ref> [[Kingsley Amis]] was also hired as a story consultant; in a letter to author Theo Richmond on 20 December 1965 Amis wrote he was having 'a horrible time' of writing an outline for Willoughby.{{sfn|Amis|2000|p=665}} [[W. H. Canaway|W.H. "Bill" Canaway]], co-author of the screenplay for [[The Ipcress File (film)|The Ipcress File]], was also hired to work on the script.<ref name="Films and Filming (1966)">{{cite journal|journal=Films and Filming|author=anonymous|title=Joe's Ian|volume=12|issue=3|year=1966|page=47}}</ref> At one point, film director [[John Boorman]] was involved.<ref name="Duns (2010)" /> Despite interest from [[Anglo-Amalgamated|Anglo-Amalgamated Film Distributors]] and Anglo Embassy Productions in early 1966, the project was shelved later that year.<ref name="Duns (2010)"/>

